# Java Code Standards

## Naming Conventions
- Classes and interfaces use `UpperCamelCase` (e.g., `UserService`, `OrderRepository`).
- Methods and variables use `lowerCamelCase` (e.g., `getUserById`, `orderId`).
- Constants use `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` (e.g., `MAX_RETRY_COUNT`).
- Package names are all lowercase, domain-reversed (e.g., `com.example.service`).
- Boolean variables and methods should read as questions: `isActive`, `hasPermission`, `canExecute`.
- Avoid abbreviations unless universally understood (`dto`, `id`, `url` are acceptable; `mgr`, `hlpr` are not).

## Class Structure
- Each class must have a single, clear responsibility (Single Responsibility Principle).
- Limit class length to 300–400 lines; extract cohesive logic into separate classes.
- Declare fields at the top, constructors next, then public methods, then private/protected helpers.
- Prefer composition over inheritance. Use inheritance only for genuine "is-a" relationships.
- Mark classes `final` when extension is not intended and not part of the API contract.

## Methods
- Methods should do one thing. If a method requires a multi-clause name (e.g., `fetchAndSaveUser`), it likely needs to be split.
- Prefer returning early (guard clauses) to deeply nested conditionals.
- Limit method length to ~30 lines. Longer methods usually indicate the need for extraction.
- Avoid passing more than 3–4 parameters. Use a parameter object or builder when you have more.
- Do not use `boolean` parameters that change method behavior — use method overloading or strategy objects.

## Error Handling
- Never silently swallow exceptions (`catch(Exception e) {}`).
- Always log the exception (not just the message) so stack traces are preserved.
- Use checked exceptions for recoverable conditions; use unchecked (runtime) exceptions for programming errors.
- Do not use exceptions for flow control.
- Wrap checked exceptions in custom domain exceptions where they cross architectural boundaries.

## Immutability & State
- Prefer immutable objects. Make fields `final` wherever possible.
- Avoid mutable static state; use dependency injection instead.
- Use `Collections.unmodifiableList` (or Guava/java.util.Collections equivalents) when returning collections that should not be modified.

## Null Handling
- Avoid returning `null` from methods. Prefer `Optional<T>` for optional return values (Java 8+).
- Never pass `null` as a method argument. Use overloading or sentinel objects instead.
- Annotate parameters and return values with `@NonNull` / `@Nullable` where the intent is non-obvious.
- Validate method arguments at entry points using `Objects.requireNonNull` or Guava `Preconditions`.

## Code Clarity
- Avoid magic numbers and magic strings. Define them as named constants.
- Prefer explicit types over `var` where the type is not immediately obvious from the right-hand side.
- Limit nested blocks to 2–3 levels; extract inner logic into named methods.
- Keep comments focused on "why", not "what". Delete commented-out code.

## Generics & Collections
- Always parameterize generic types; avoid raw types.
- Use the most abstract type in declarations (`List<>` over `ArrayList<>` in method signatures).
- Stream API is preferred over manual loops for data transformation, but avoid deeply chained streams that hurt readability.

## Thread Safety
- Mark shared mutable state clearly and protect it with appropriate synchronization or concurrent data structures.
- Document thread-safety guarantees in class-level Javadoc.
- Prefer `java.util.concurrent` constructs (`AtomicReference`, `ConcurrentHashMap`, `ReentrantLock`) over raw `synchronized` blocks.
